The speed profile is of a considerable interest when examining fluid motion, where it gives many details about the flow field. Therefore, Figs. 2, 3, 4, 5 are plotted to display the changes of the radial as well as azimuthal velocities versus the axis of the disk for various standards of the substantial limitation of the Reiner–Rivlin fluid K\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$K$$\end{document} and the magnetic factor M\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$M$$\end{document}. It is found that the radial and azimuthal velocities increase near the disk and attain maximum values at a short distance away, and then they decrease as they move far away from it to vanish at the free stream. In details, it is understood from Figs. 2 and 3 that the radial and azimuthal velocities decrease with the rise in the value of K\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$K$$\end{document}. Physically, the non-Newtonian factor K\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$K$$\end{document}, as an amount of an additional viscosity of the liquid, increases the viscosity, and hence decreases the fluid velocity. Figures 4 and 5 indicate that the radial and azimuthal velocities drop by the rise of the magnetic factor M\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$M$$\end{document}. Materially, this happens owing to the development of the Lorentz force that obstructs the liquid movement; therefore, the fluid velocity decreases. These results are in accord with those earlier obtained2,3,35,41.

